'Lysozymes', also known as muramidase or 'N-acetylmuramide glycanhydrolase', are
glycoside hydrolases. These are enzymes () that damage bacterial cell walls by
catalyzing hydrolysis of 1,4-beta-linkages between N-acetylmuramic acid and N-acetyl-D-
glucosamine residues in a peptidoglycan and between N-acetyl-D-glucosamine
residues in chitodextrins. Lysozyme is abundant in a number of secretions, such
as tears, saliva, human milk, and mucus. It is also present in cytoplasmic
granules of the polymorphonuclear neutrophils (PMN). Large amounts of lysozyme
can be found in egg white. C-type lysozymes are closely related to alpha-
lactalbumin in sequence and structure, making them part of the same family.

In humans, the lysozyme enzyme is encoded by the LYZ gene.
